---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — Leslie Baynes"
  description="Biography, research, and teaching of Leslie Baynes, Professor of Religious Studies at Missouri State University."
  activePage="about"
>

  <section class="about-hero">
    <div class="about-text">
      <div class="section-label">About</div>
      <h1>About Leslie Baynes</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Leslie Baynes is a scholar of the New Testament and Second Temple Judaism whose work ranges
        from the apocalyptic literature of the ancient world to the Christian imagination of the
        twentieth century. She is Professor of Religious Studies at Missouri State University,
        where she has taught since 2005.
      </p>
      <p>
        Her most recent book, <em>Between Interpretation and Imagination: C. S. Lewis and the
        Bible</em> (Eerdmans, 2025), is the first full-length study of how Lewis read Scripture
        &mdash; drawing on previously unpublished marginalia from his personal library. Michael
        Ward of Oxford has called it &ldquo;easily the best book yet written on Lewis and
        Scripture.&rdquo;
      </p>
      <p>
        Her first book, <em>The Heavenly Book Motif in Judeo-Christian Apocalypses 200
        BCE&ndash;200 CE</em> (Brill, 2012), established her work in the field of ancient
        apocalyptic literature, where she continues to write on 1 Enoch, the Book of Revelation,
        and the reception history of biblical texts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Leslie served as a translator for the New American Bible Revised Edition &mdash; the
        English translation used in Catholic liturgy across the United States. She contributed to
        the New Testament&rsquo;s Johannine books: the Gospel, Epistles, and Revelation of John.
        The translation was approved for liturgical use by the Dicastery for Divine Worship in
        June 2025.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-image">
      <img src="/images/headshot-hero.jpg" alt="Portrait of Leslie Baynes" loading="eager" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="section-divider">
    <span class="ornament">&#9753;</span>
  </div>

  <section class="origin">
    <h2>A biblical scholar, in short</h2>
    <p>
      Leslie&rsquo;s scholarly life began in an unlikely place. She didn&rsquo;t own a Bible until
      she was fourteen. As a college student at the University of Dayton, she chose English for her
      major because her parents considered religious studies impractical &mdash; though she minored
      in it anyway, and read classical Greek on the side because she loved the language.
    </p>
    <p>
      She earned her Ph.D. in Christianity and Judaism in Antiquity at the University of Notre Dame
      in 2005, taught at Notre Dame briefly, and joined the faculty at Missouri State the same
      year. She has been there ever since.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2014 she was named Scholar-in-Residence at The Kilns &mdash; C. S. Lewis&rsquo;s home
      outside Oxford &mdash; a residency that seeded the book that would become <em>Between
      Interpretation and Imagination</em> a decade later. In 2023 she was selected for the
      inaugural cohort of Inklings Project Fellows at the University of Notre Dame&rsquo;s McGrath
      Institute for Church Life. She was promoted to Professor of Religious Studies in 2026.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="service">
    <h2>Research and professional service</h2>
    <p>
      Her ongoing research sits at the intersection of several fields: Second Temple Judaism,
      apocalyptic literature, the Book of Revelation, 1 Enoch, reception history, and C. S. Lewis.
      Her current projects include a chapter for <em>The Fourth Gospel and Revelation as Johannine
      Literature</em> (Bloomsbury T&amp;T Clark) and the introduction and annotations to the Book
      of Revelation for <em>The Ancient Christian Study Bible</em>, forthcoming from Oxford
      University Press.
    </p>
    <p>
      She serves on the advisory board of <em>St. Vladimir&rsquo;s Theological Quarterly</em> and
      the editorial board of <em>Texts and Studies in the Ethiopic Bible and Related Literature</em>.
      She is co-chair of the Biblical Exegesis from Eastern Orthodox Perspectives section at the
      Society of Biblical Literature.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="teaching">
    <h2>Courses taught</h2>
    <p>
      At Missouri State, Leslie teaches New Testament, Jesus of Nazareth, Apocalypses, C. S. Lewis,
      and Catholicism, along with graduate seminars on biblical interpretation, the Book of
      Revelation and its afterlives, and Genesis 1&ndash;3. She has led two study-away courses:
      <em>Pagans and Christians</em> in Italy and <em>Jack and Joy in Oxford: C. S. Lewis at
      Home</em> in England.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="cv-cta">
    <div class="cv-cta-inner">
      <div>
        <h3>Full publication list and academic history</h3>
        <p>Complete CV available as a downloadable PDF.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/cv-leslie-baynes.pdf" class="btn">Download CV</a>
    </div>
  </section>

</Base>

<style>
  .about-hero {
    max-width: var(--max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 80px 48px 100px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1.4fr 1fr;
    gap: 80px;
    align-items: start;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .about-hero {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      padding: 48px 24px 60px;
      gap: 48px;
    }
  }

  .about-text h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(44px, 5.5vw, 72px);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 144, "SOFT" 40, "WONK" 1;
    line-height: 1.05;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-top: 24px;
    margin-bottom: 36px;
  }

  .about-text .lede {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(20px, 2vw, 24px);
    font-weight: 300;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 60;
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-bottom: 28px;
  }

  .about-text p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }

  .about-image {
    aspect-ratio: 4/5;
    overflow: hidden;
    border-radius: 2px;
    box-shadow:
      0 20px 40px rgba(35, 28, 21, 0.12),
      0 40px 80px rgba(35, 28, 21, 0.08);
    position: sticky;
    top: 40px;
  }

  .about-image img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center 18%;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .about-image { position: static; }
  }

  .origin, .service, .teaching {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 80px 48px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .origin, .service, .teaching { padding: 60px 24px; }
  }

  .origin h2, .service h2, .teaching h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(30px, 3.4vw, 40px);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 144, "SOFT" 30;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 36px;
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
  }

  .origin p, .service p, .teaching p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }

  .cv-cta {
    background: var(--ivory-deep);
    padding: 80px 48px;
    margin-top: 40px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .cv-cta { padding: 60px 24px; }
  }

  .cv-cta-inner {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 32px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .cv-cta h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 400;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 144;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .cv-cta p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    font-size: 16px;
  }
</style>
